I&#x27;m quite surprised by Rust behaviour here: if x isn&#x27;t used after &#x27;v.push(6);&#x27; (doesn&#x27;t seem too difficult to know by the compiler) then I would have expected the compiler to allow this code and to reject it only if x is used after the &#x27;v.push(6)&#x27;..
Sure as he explained you can do 
&quot;let mut v = vec![1i32, 2, 3, 4, 5];
{
  let x = v.get(2);
  <work with x>
}
v.push(6);&quot;
but this must be quite annoying..
